Additionally, the paper mentions the use of surface normal priors derived from Manhattan-world assumptions, which is a common technique in computer vision. 

The paper may also belong to the Graphics (cs.GR) sub-category as it deals with 3D scene reconstruction, which is a common problem in computer graphics. 

The Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category is also a possibility as stereo matching is an important problem in robotics for tasks such as obstacle avoidance and localization. 

The Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category is a possibility as stereo matching is a fundamental problem in computer vision, which is a subfield of AI. 

Finally, the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category is a possibility as the paper mentions the use of priors, which can be seen as a form of regularization, a common technique in machine learning.
